## Pre-Upgrade Checklist

- [ ] Remove the conflicting `aks-managed-*` tags (see Step 1 below)
- [ ] Confirm valid Kubernetes versions available in your region (see Step 2)
- [ ] Schedule upgrade during a low-traffic maintenance window
- [ ] Ensure workloads have `PodDisruptionBudgets` configured to avoid downtime during node drain
- [ ] Back up any critical workload configurations
- [ ] Confirm `kubectl` is connected to the correct cluster context
- [ ] Notify stakeholders of the maintenance window

-----

## Step 1 — Remove Conflicting Tags (Required Before Upgrade)

Running the upgrade will fail with a `BadRequest` error if the cluster has any tags prefixed with `aks-managed-`. Two such tags were found on this cluster:

```json
{
  "aks-managed-cluster-name": "developer-k8s-cluster",
  "aks-managed-cluster-rg": "rg_vnet_developer"
}
```

**View current tags:**

```bash
az aks show \
  --resource-group rg_vnet_developer \
  --name developer-k8s-cluster \
  --query tags
```

**Remove both conflicting tags:**

```bash
az tag update \
  --resource-id $(az aks show \
    --resource-group rg_vnet_developer \
    --name developer-k8s-cluster \
    --query id -o tsv) \
  --operation Delete \
  --tags aks-managed-cluster-name="" aks-managed-cluster-rg=""
```

**Verify tags are gone** (should return `{}` or `null`):

```bash
az aks show \
  --resource-group rg_vnet_developer \
  --name developer-k8s-cluster \
  --query tags
```

> ⚠️ **Going forward**, avoid any tags starting with `aks-managed-` on AKS resources. Use non-reserved names like `cluster-name` and `cluster-rg` instead.

-----

## Step 2 — Confirm Valid Versions in Your Region

Before upgrading node pools, always verify which versions are actually available in your region. Specifying an invalid patch version (e.g. `1.31.14`) will result in a `K8sVersionNotSupported` error.

**Get your cluster’s region:**

```bash
az aks show \
  --resource-group rg_vnet_developer \
  --name developer-k8s-cluster \
  --query location -o tsv
```

**List all valid versions for that region:**

```bash
az aks get-versions \
  --location <your-region> \
  --output table
```

> Always pick a valid `1.31.x` patch from this output before running node pool upgrades. Do not guess patch numbers.

-----

## Step 3 — Upgrade the Control Plane

```bash
az aks upgrade \
  --resource-group rg_vnet_developer \
  --name developer-k8s-cluster \
  --kubernetes-version 1.32.10 \
  --control-plane-only
```

When prompted, type `y` for both confirmations:

- *“Kubernetes may be unavailable during cluster upgrades. Are you sure? (y/N)”*
- *“This will upgrade only the control plane to 1.32.10. Continue? (y/N)”*

> Using `--control-plane-only` allows node pools to be upgraded separately on your own schedule. The `davepool` and `system` node pools will not be touched.

**Expected duration:** 5–15 minutes

**Monitor progress in a second terminal:**

```bash
watch -n 10 az aks show \
  --resource-group rg_vnet_developer \
  --name developer-k8s-cluster \
  --query "{state:provisioningState, version:kubernetesVersion}" \
  --output table
```

You will see `provisioningState` transition: `Upgrading` → `Succeeded`

-----

## Step 4 — Upgrade the `system` Node Pool

> ⚠️ **The `system` pool is on `1.30.14` — two minor versions behind.** AKS only supports one minor version jump at a time. You must upgrade to a valid `1.31.x` first, then to `1.32.10`.

**First hop — upgrade to a valid 1.31.x (confirm version from Step 2):**

```bash
az aks nodepool upgrade \
  --resource-group rg_vnet_developer \
  --cluster-name developer-k8s-cluster \
  --name system \
  --kubernetes-version 1.31.X   # ← replace X with valid patch from az aks get-versions
```

**Second hop — upgrade to 1.32.10:**

```bash
az aks nodepool upgrade \
  --resource-group rg_vnet_developer \
  --cluster-name developer-k8s-cluster \
  --name system \
  --kubernetes-version 1.32.10
```

> The `system` node pool runs critical cluster services (CoreDNS, metrics server, etc.). Verify cluster stability after each hop before proceeding.

-----

## Step 5 — Upgrade the `davepool` Node Pool

`davepool` is only one minor version behind (`1.31.10`) so it can jump directly to `1.32.10`.

```bash
az aks nodepool upgrade \
  --resource-group rg_vnet_developer \
  --cluster-name developer-k8s-cluster \
  --name davepool \
  --kubernetes-version 1.32.10
```

**Optional — speed up with Max Surge** (brings up a new node before draining the old one):

```bash
az aks nodepool upgrade \
  --resource-group rg_vnet_developer \
  --cluster-name developer-k8s-cluster \
  --name davepool \
  --kubernetes-version 1.32.10 \
  --max-surge 1
```

-----

## Step 6 — Verify the Upgrade

```bash
# Check control plane version
az aks show \
  --resource-group rg_vnet_developer \
  --name developer-k8s-cluster \
  --output table

# Check all node pools
az aks nodepool list \
  --resource-group rg_vnet_developer \
  --cluster-name developer-k8s-cluster \
  --output table
```

All components should show version `1.32.10` and `ProvisioningState: Succeeded`.

-----

## Upgrade Order Summary

```
1. Remove aks-managed-cluster-name and aks-managed-cluster-rg tags
2. Confirm valid 1.31.x versions via az aks get-versions
3. Upgrade control plane        → 1.32.10   (--control-plane-only)
4. Upgrade system pool          → 1.31.x    (intermediate hop - use valid patch)
5. Upgrade system pool          → 1.32.10   (final hop)
6. Upgrade davepool             → 1.32.10   (single hop)
7. Verify all components on 1.32.10
```

-----

## Known Errors & Fixes

|Error                                              |Cause                                |Fix                                                                     |
|---------------------------------------------------|-------------------------------------|------------------------------------------------------------------------|
|`BadRequest: aks-managed-cluster-rg is not allowed`|Reserved AKS tag on cluster          |Remove all `aks-managed-*` tags using `az tag update --operation Delete`|
|`K8sVersionNotSupported: invalid version 1.31.14`  |Patch version doesn’t exist in region|Run `az aks get-versions --location <region>` and use a valid patch     |

-----

## Notes

- Node pools are **cordoned and drained** during upgrade — pods are rescheduled to available nodes
- Monitor the Azure Portal under **Kubernetes service → Node pools** for visual progress
- The `system` node pool must be upgraded carefully — it hosts core cluster services
- Do not skip the intermediate `1.31.x` hop for the `system` pool; AKS will reject it
- Available versions vary by region — always verify with `az aks get-versions` before upgrading
